{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #450: declared status 'open'. Formalized: no. How large must $y=y(\\epsilon,n)$ be such that the number of integers in $(x,x+y)$ with a divisor in $(n,2n)$ is at most $\\epsilon y$? Current best: On the other hand, Cambie has observed that if $\\epsilon\\ll 1/n$ then $y(\\epsilon,n)\\sim 2n$: indeed, if $y<2n$ then this is impossible taking $x+n$ to be a multiple of the lowest common multiple of $\\{n+1,\\ldots,2n-1\\}$. Prize: no. Tags: divisors, number theory.","id":"vf_16fb06b1326a3d95","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: FC 450 (PR #4072) [in-pr] https://github.com/google-deepmind/formal-conjectures/pull/4072.","id":"vf_5a4b02e89d7feea0","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/450.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_16fb06b1326a3d95","source_root":"sha256:540d4967071425f77c693e61f62053208b07d67667490dcb9eeef62ec3f1d316","target":"erdos:450","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_5a4b02e89d7feea0","source_root":"sha256:540d4967071425f77c693e61f62053208b07d67667490dcb9eeef62ec3f1d316","target":"erdos:450","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_from","source":"vf_5a4b02e89d7feea0","source_root":"sha256:540d4967071425f77c693e61f62053208b07d67667490dcb9eeef62ec3f1d316","target":"vf_16fb06b1326a3d95","trust":"signed"}],"external_references":[],"formal_conjectures_activity":null,"frontier_id":"vfr_0a25edabc16db143","frontier_root":"sha256:540d4967071425f77c693e61f62053208b07d676674